{"entries":[{"caption":"Rare genes in the SARA cohort.","key":"tbl-rare_genes","order":{"number":2,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Boxplots show the distribution of onset ages for each diagnosis, including minimum, maximum, and interquartile ranges. The vertical black line in each box represents the median age of onset, while blue dots indicate the mean, and red dots indicate the minimum observed onset for each diagnosis. Many IRDs exhibit early onset, typically in childhood or adolescence, whereas others—such as USH, macular dystrophy, STGD, DOA, and RP—display broader or later-onset distributions.","key":"fig-s-age-onset-pheno","order":{"number":2,"section":[0,2,0,2,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Number of distinct disease-associated genes identified for each inherited retinal disease diagnosis in the SARA cohort. While many phenotypes were associated with one or two genes, others—most notably retinitis pigmentosa, Leber congenital amaurosis, and cone–rod dystrophy—exhibited marked genetic heterogeneity, reflecting variable molecular architectures across IRDs.","key":"fig-s-gene_dx","order":{"number":7,"section":[0,4,0,2,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Matrix representation of previously reported genetic variants observed five or more times in the SARA database. The figure highlights 34 unique recurrent variants distributed across 14 genes, annotated at both the DNA and protein levels.","key":"fig-s-reported_variants","order":{"number":4,"section":[0,2,0,4,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Matrix representation of low-frequency Dx–Gene associations contributing to less than 1% of genetically resolved cases. This long-tail component captures a broad spectrum of rare and pleiotropic relationships across multiple diagnoses and genes, illustrating the extensive molecular and phenotypic diversity underlying inherited retinal diseases.","key":"fig-s-DxGeneB","order":{"number":9,"section":[0,4,0,4,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Matrix representation of Dx–Gene associations accounting for at least 1% of genetically resolved cases. Tiles indicate the number of patients contributing to each diagnosis–gene combination. This compact core highlights a limited set of recurrent relationships that explain a substantial fraction of the cohort and correspond to well-established IRD genes and phenotypes.","key":"fig-s-DxGeneA","order":{"number":8,"section":[0,4,0,3,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Top 20 clinical phenotypes in the merged SARA + SPG et.al (2023) cohort, calculated at the patient level. Each patient was counted once per phenotype, regardless of the number of associated variants. Percentages are reported relative to the total number of patients with a defined clinical phenotype in each cohort (merged, SARA only, and SPG et. al, only). The 20 most frequent phenotypes accounted for 98.3% of patients with a defined clinical phenotype in the merged cohort.","key":"tbl-NW-pheno","order":{"number":4,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Multigenic findings. Eighteen cases carried pathogenic or likely pathogenic variants in more than one IRD-associated gene. For each patient, the implicated genes and the patient´s phenotype are shown.","key":"tbl-multigene","order":{"number":3,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The assigned modes of inheritance for IRD genes in the SARA cohort","key":"tbl-ModeInher","order":{"number":7,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Distribution of unique genetic variants by recurrence level in the SARA cohort, stratified by previously reported (R) and novel (N) status. Bars indicate the number of unique variants within each recurrence class; high-frequency classes (\\geq 10 observations) are collapsed for clarity. Novel variants are largely confined to singleton and low-frequency classes, whereas previously reported variants span a broader recurrence spectrum, including highly recurrent alleles.","key":"fig-s-rec-tail","order":{"number":3,"section":[0,2,0,3,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Acronyms, phenotypes, numbers and percentages of patients included in the cohort.","key":"tbl-phenotypes","order":{"number":1,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Distribution of the number of phenotypes associated with each disease-associated gene in the SARA cohort. Most genes were linked to a single phenotype, while a non-negligible fraction contributed to two or more diagnoses, illustrating widespread genetic pleiotropy beyond high-frequency loci. Counts refer to genes with at least one assigned clinical diagnosis.","key":"fig-s-dx-gene","order":{"number":6,"section":[0,4,0,1,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Distribution of age of clinical onset in the SARA cohort. Histogram of age at clinical onset among all genetically resolved individuals. The distribution ranged from 1 month to 73 years and was right-skewed. The mode was 15 years, the median was 19.5 years, and the mean was 25.7 years. The interquartile range extended from 11 years (Q1) to 39 years (Q3), indicating that half of all cases developed symptoms within the first four decades of life.","key":"fig-s-age-onset","order":{"number":1,"section":[0,2,0,1,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Top 20 disease-associated genes in the merged SARA–SPG et.al cohort, calculated at the patient level. Each patient was counted once per gene, irrespective of the number of reported variants. Percentages are reported relative to the total number of patients with at least one reported gene in each cohort (merged, SARA only, and SPG et.al, only). The 20 most frequently involved genes accounted for 80.0% of patients with at least one reported disease-associated gene.","key":"tbl-NW-genes","order":{"number":5,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Distribution of novel variants across the most frequently affected genes. Matrix depicting novel genetic variants across the 25 genes with the highest burden of newly identified variants in the SARA cohort.","key":"fig-s-novel_variants","order":{"number":5,"section":[0,2,0,5,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"","key":"tbl-genetic_rules","order":{"number":6,"section":[0,3,0,0,0,0,0]}}],"headings":["supp-methods","genetic-analysis-and-sequencing-strategy","bioinformatic-processing-and-variant-detection","comprehensive-variant-annotation-using-local-vep-analysis","rule-based-framework-for-genetic-case-resolution","definition-of-resolution-categories","description-of-the-resolution-rules","autosomal-recessive-ar","autosomal-dominant-ad","x-linked-xl","autosomal-recessive-autosomal-dominant-arad","mitochondrial-mt","frequency-based-extensions","summary-of-cases-per-resolution-rule","data-harmonisation-and-statistical-analysis","supplementary-figures","age-at-clinical-onset","age-of-onset-across-ird-diagnoses","recurrence-spectrum","matrix-of-reported-variants","matrix-of-novel-variants","supplementary-tables","supp-dx-gene-architecture","distribution-of-diagnoses-per-gene-pleiotropy","genetic-heterogeneity-across-ird-diagnoses","core-pheno-gene-architecture-of-the-sara-cohort-1-associations","long-tail-pheno-gene-architecture-of-the-sara-cohort-1-associations","supplementary-data-files","supp-df-s1"],"options":{"fig-prefix":"Supplementary Figure","fig-title":"Supplementary Figure","tbl-prefix":"Supplementary Table"}}